    "answer_id" : 1686713,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>You can't do this yourself since Java doesn't permit operator overloading. </p>\n\n<p>With <em>one</em> exception, however. <strong>+</strong> and <strong>+=</strong> are overloaded for String objects.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 28119,
      "reputation" : 15484,
      "user_id" : 74772,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 82,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/11d23737853fe8479be8f026cc64f9b1?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "teabot",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/74772/teabot"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 38,
    "last_activity_date" : 1257503152,
    "creation_date" : 1257503152,
    "answer_id" : 1686714,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Operator overloading is used in Java for the concatenation of the String type:</p>\n\n<pre><code>String concat = \"one\" + \"two\";\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>However, you <strong>cannot</strong> define your own operator overloads.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 2031,
        "reputation" : 3764,
