    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Java does not allow operator overloading. The preferred approach is to define a method on your class to perform the action: <code>a.add(b)</code> instead of <code>a + b</code>. You can see a summary of the other bits Java left out from C like languages here: <a href=\"http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/simple-142616.html\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Features Removed from C and C++</a></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 8519,
      "reputation" : 181725,
      "user_id" : 15416,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 63,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/a2b11b9662b5155aada74191fbe7cb9e?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "MSalters",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/15416/msalters"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 27,
    "last_activity_date" : 1421748827,
    "last_edit_date" : 1421748827,
    "creation_date" : 1257503919,
    "answer_id" : 1686782,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In addition to all the people pointing out that <code>+</code> is overloaded for Strings, <code>-</code> is also overloaded for both floating point and integer operations, as are <code>*</code> and <code>/</code>. </p>\n\n<p>[edit]\n<code>%</code> is also overloaded for floating point, which can be a bit of a surprise for those with a C or C++ background.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 920239,
      "reputation" : 3102,
      "user_id" : 952041,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/73c94c3cdb50eece7dd7107118d1bed2?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Alexander Mironov",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/952041/alexander-mironov"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 12,
    "last_activity_date" : 1370718810,
    "creation_date" : 1370718810,
    "answer_id" : 17002930,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>One can try <a href=\"https://github.com/amelentev/java-oo\" rel=\"noreferrer\">Java Operator Overloading</a>. It has its own limitations, but it worth trying if you really want to use operator overloading.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 3156791,
      "reputation" : 158,
      "user_id" : 2669023,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da12070dcbd7ed2f9eb356e97c3c985b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Aurelien B",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2669023/aurelien-b"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 9,
    "last_activity_date" : 1376076218,
    "creation_date" : 1376076218,
    "answer_id" : 18154176,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Just use Xtend along with your Java code. It supports Operator Overloading:</p>\n\n<pre><code>    package com.example;\n\n@SuppressWarnings(\"all\")\npublic class Test {\n  protected int wrapped;\n\n  public Test(final int value) {\n    this.wrapped = value;\n  }\n\n  public int operator_plus(final Test e2) {\n    return (this.wrapped + e2.wrapped);\n  }\n}\n\npackage com.example\n\nclass Test2 {\n\n    new() {\n        val t1 = new Test(3)\n        val t2 = new Test(5)\n        val t3 = t1 + t2\n    }\n\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>On the official website, there is a list of the methods to implement for each operator !</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 2139574,
      "reputation" : 2044,
      "user_id" : 2474098,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 69,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/511dff23b9073611ae2728779f2b3c85?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "alknows",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2474098/alknows"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 5,
    "last_activity_date" : 1434636359,
    "last_edit_date" : 1434636359,
    "creation_date" : 1386522866,
    "answer_id" : 20456338,
    "question_id" : 1686699,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Or, you can make Java <strong>Groovy</strong> and just overload these functions to achieve what you want</p>\n\n<pre><code>//plus() =&gt; for the + operator\n//multiply() =&gt; for the * operator\n//leftShift() = for the &lt;&lt; operator\n// ... and so on ...\n\nclass Fish {\n    def leftShift(Fish fish) {\n        print \"You just &lt;&lt; (left shifted) some fish \"\n    }\n}\n\n\ndef fish = new Fish()\ndef fish2 = new Fish()\n\nfish &lt;&lt; fish2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Who doesnt want to be/use groovy? :D</p>\n\n<p>No you cannot use the compiled groovy JARs in Java the same way. It still is a compiler error for Java.</p>\n"
  }, {
